Chapter 5: Exposing Non-HTTP/SNI Applications
Goal
Expose applications to external access without using an ingress controller.
Normally OpenShift exposes applications using Routes, but routes work only for HTTP/HTTPS traffic.
Some protocols cannot use routes, so we use other mechanisms like:
1.	LoadBalancer Services
2.	Secondary Networks (Multus)
________________________________________
1. Why Routes and Ingress Are Not Always Enough
OpenShift Routes and Kubernetes Ingress work mainly for:
•	HTTP
•	HTTPS
•	TLS with SNI
Example:
https://app.example.com
Router uses the hostname to route traffic.
Example routing:
https://a.example.com → Service A
https://b.example.com → Service B
This works because HTTP supports virtual hosting.
________________________________________
2. Protocols That Cannot Use Routes
Many protocols do not support virtual hosting or SNI.
Examples:
Protocol	Example Port
SSH	22
MySQL	3306
LDAP	389
SMTP	25
POP3	110
IMAP	143
Example service:
SSH server
IP: 1.2.3.4
Port: 22
Clients must connect directly:
1.2.3.4:22
Routes cannot expose these.
________________________________________
3. Solution: Kubernetes Services
Kubernetes provides Service resources to expose pods.
Pods are dynamic:
•	Pods may restart
•	Pods may scale
•	Pods may move nodes
Users cannot rely on pod IP addresses.
Services provide:
•	Stable IP
•	Stable port
•	Internal load balancing
________________________________________
4. Service Components
A Kubernetes Service contains:
Component	Purpose
selector	identifies pods
port	service port
targetPort	pod port
Example:
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: example
spec:
  selector:
    app: example
  ports:
  - port: 80
    targetPort: 8080
________________________________________
5. Types of Kubernetes Services
There are four main service types.
Service Type	Purpose
ClusterIP	internal access
NodePort	external access via node
LoadBalancer	external load balancer
ExternalIP	manual external IP
________________________________________
6. ClusterIP Service
Default service type.
Accessible only inside cluster.
Example architecture:
Pod A
   │
   ▼
Service (ClusterIP)
   │
   ▼
Pod B
Pod C
Pod D
Example:
spec:
  type: ClusterIP
Example service IP:
172.30.21.79
Pods connect via:
http://service-name
or
http://service-name.namespace.svc
________________________________________
7. NodePort Service
Exposes service on each node IP + port.
Architecture:
External User
     │
     ▼
NodeIP:NodePort
     │
     ▼
ClusterIP Service
     │
     ▼
Pods
Example:
192.168.1.10:30001
NodePort range:
30000 – 32767
Example YAML:
spec:
  type: NodePort
  ports:
  - port: 80
    nodePort: 30001
________________________________________
8. LoadBalancer Service
Used to expose services directly with an external IP.
Architecture:
Internet
   │
   ▼
Cloud Load Balancer
   │
   ▼
Kubernetes Service
   │
   ▼
Pods
Example YAML:
spec:
  type: LoadBalancer
Example output:
NAME         TYPE           CLUSTER-IP      EXTERNAL-IP
example-lb   LoadBalancer   172.30.21.79    192.168.50.20
Users connect:
192.168.50.20:1234
________________________________________
