10. Load Balancer in Bare-Metal Clusters
On bare metal, Kubernetes cannot create cloud load balancers.
Solution:
MetalLB
________________________________________
11. MetalLB
MetalLB is a software load balancer for bare-metal clusters.
It assigns external IP addresses to services.
Example:
LoadBalancer Service
      │
      ▼
MetalLB
      │
      ▼
External IP assigned
Example IP:
192.168.50.20
________________________________________
12. MetalLB Modes
MetalLB works in two networking modes.
________________________________________
1️⃣ Layer 2 Mode (ARP)
Default mode.
Uses ARP announcements.
This mode uses Address Resolution Protocol (ARP).
ARP is used in local networks to find which machine owns an IP.
Example in a normal LAN:
Who has 192.168.1.10?
The device replies:
I have 192.168.1.10
How MetalLB Uses ARP
MetalLB picks one Kubernetes node to advertise the IP.
Example:
Service IP = 192.168.50.20
MetalLB chooses Node2
Now Node2 tells the network:
192.168.50.20 is me
So traffic goes to Node2.
Example:
LoadBalancer IP = 192.168.50.20
Node advertises IP via ARP
Traffic sent to that node
Flow:
Client
  │
  ▼
Node (advertising IP)
  │
  ▼
Service
  │
  ▼
Pod
Advantages:
•	Simple
•	Works without router configuration
________________________________________
2️⃣ Layer 3 Mode (BGP)
Uses Border Gateway Protocol.
Routers learn service IP routes.
This mode uses Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
BGP is the protocol routers use to exchange routes on the internet.
Instead of ARP announcements, nodes tell the router:
Route to 192.168.50.20 through me
How It Works
Nodes speak BGP with the router.
Example router:
Router
  │
  ├── Node1
  ├── Node2
  └── Node3

All nodes advertise the service IP.

Node1 → route 192.168.50.20
Node2 → route 192.168.50.20
Node3 → route 192.168.50.20

The router then balances traffic between them.
Flow:
Router
  │
  ▼
Node
  │
  ▼
Service
  │
  ▼
Pods
Requirements:
•	Router BGP configuration
•	Autonomous System Number (ASN)
Advantages:
•	More scalable
•	Better load distribution
________________________________________
13. MetalLB Operator
MetalLB is installed via Operator Lifecycle Manager (OLM).
After installation, it creates resources in:
metallb-system namespace
Example command:
oc get metallb -n metallb-system
Output:
NAME     AGE
metallb  7d
________________________________________
14. MetalLB Important Resources
1️⃣ IPAddressPool
Defines IP range used for services.
Example:
oc get ipaddresspool -n metallb-system
Example output:
NAME                      ADDRESSES
metallb-ip-pool           192.168.50.20-192.168.50.40
________________________________________
2️⃣ L2Advertisement
Advertises IPs using ARP.
Example:
oc get l2advertisement -n metallb-system
Output:
NAME                       IPADDRESSPOOLS
metallb-l2                 metallb-ip-pool
________________________________________
15. Creating LoadBalancer Service
Example YAML:
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: example-lb
spec:
  selector:
    name: example
  ports:
  - port: 1234
    targetPort: 1234
  type: LoadBalancer
________________________________________
16. Imperative Command
You can create it using CLI.
oc expose deployment example \
--port=1234 \
--type=LoadBalancer
________________________________________
17. Checking External IP
oc get service
Example:
NAME         TYPE           CLUSTER-IP       EXTERNAL-IP
example-lb   LoadBalancer   172.30.21.79     192.168.50.20
________________________________________
18. Retrieve IP via JSONPath
oc get example-lb -o jsonpath="{.status.loadBalancer.ingress}"
Output:
[{"ip":"192.168.50.20"}]
